{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <h1>Routing</h1>
    <p>
        The router is the heart of the Rhapsody framework. It maps incoming browser requests to specific controller methods, allowing you to create clean, human-readable URLs. All routes for your web application are defined in the <code>/routes/web.php</code> and <code>/routes/api.php</code> files.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Basic Routing</h2>
    <p>
        The most basic route accepts a URI and a callback. The callback is typically an array containing the controller class and the method name to execute. You can define routes for different HTTP methods like GET and POST.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">// routes/web.php
use App\Controllers\PageController;
use Rhapsody\Core\Routing\Router;

// A GET route that shows the about page
Router::get('/about', [PageController::class, 'about']);

// A POST route that handles a form submission
Router::post('/contact', [PageController::class, 'handleContact']);</code></pre>

    <h2>Dynamic Routes with Parameters</h2>
    <p>
        Often, you'll need to capture segments of the URI, such as a user ID or a blog post slug. You can do this by defining route parameters enclosed in curly braces <code>{}</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
        These captured parameters are automatically passed as arguments to your controller method, in the order they appear.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">// Route definition
Router::get('/users/{user_id}', [PageController::class, 'viewUser']);

// Controller method
public function viewUser(Request $request, string $user_id)
{
    $user = (new User())->getUserById($user_id);
    // ...
}</code></pre>
    <p><strong>Important:</strong> The router always passes the <code>Rhapsody\Core\Request</code> object as the first argument to your controller method, followed by any dynamic route parameters.</p>

    <h2>Named Routes &amp; URL Generation</h2>
    <p>
        Rhapsody supports <strong>named routes</strong>, allowing you to generate URLs dynamically without hardcoding paths. This is especially useful when your application is installed in a subdirectory.
    </p>
    <p>
        To assign a name to a route, chain the <code>name()</code> method:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">Router::get('/profile/{id}', [ProfileController::class, 'show'])->name('profile.show');</code></pre>
    <p>
        You can then generate URLs using the <code>route()</code> Twig function in your views:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&lt;a href="&lcub;&lcub; route('profile.show', {id: user.id}) }}"&gt;View Profile&lt;/a&gt;</code></pre>
    <p>
        The <code>route()</code> function accepts the route name as the first argument and an optional associative array of parameters to replace the placeholders.
    </p>
    <p>
        If you need the base URL (including subdirectory) prepended, the <code>route()</code> function automatically uses <code>$_ENV['APP_URL'] . $_ENV['APP_BASE_URL']</code>.
    </p>
    <p>
        You can also generate URLs from PHP using the static method <code>Router::generateUrl($name, $params)</code>.
    </p>

    <h2>Middleware</h2>
    <p>
        You can attach middleware to routes to filter requests (e.g., authentication, CSRF protection). Middleware are resolved from the container and executed before the controller.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">Router::get('/dashboard', [DashboardController::class, 'index'])
    ->middleware('auth'); // only authenticated users</code></pre>
    <p>
        Middleware can be defined in the <code>config.php</code> file under the <code>middleware.map</code> key.
    </p>

    <h2>Container Integration</h2>
    <p>
        The router uses the service container to resolve controllers and their dependencies. Your controller classes can type‑hint any service, and the container will inject them automatically. The router also accepts a <code>ContainerInterface</code> instance, allowing you to swap the container implementation if needed.
    </p>
    <p>
        For performance, the container can be configured to lazy‑load services (see the <a href="{{ base_url }}/docs/performance">Performance</a> documentation).
    </p>

    <h2>Debugging Routes</h2>
    <p>
        The debug toolbar includes a <strong>Services</strong> and <strong>Middleware</strong> panel that show which routes were matched, which middleware were executed, and which services were resolved during the request. This is invaluable for profiling and debugging.
    </p>

    <h2>Social Login (OAuth)</h2>
    <p>
        Rhapsody includes built‑in support for social authentication via Google and Facebook. See the <a href="{{ base_url }}/docs/social-auth">Social Authentication</a> documentation for setup instructions and route examples.
    </p>

{% endblock %}